The '''Kuchu Collective''' is a [[non governmental organization]] that aims to promote and protect [[LGBTI]] [[rights]] in sub-Saharan Africa by developing and actively encouraging use of technological tools and materials, that shield LGBTI persons and activists against [[hate groups]], repressive [[governments]] and their institutions .<ref>Kuchu Collective. [http://kuchucollective.com/ Our Mission]. Retrieved 2015-7-18</ref>
==Activities== * The Kuchu Collective Yamba android app . [http://kuchucollective.com.s3-website.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/workDetails.html Yamba] * Twifrica.<ref>Using an automated Twitter-based api system to report incidents of violence against sexual minorities so the crowd can act.</ref> * Summer Source Camp, open source workshop.<ref>Paul-Brian McInerney. "Technology Movements and the Politics of Free/Open Source Software." Science Technology Human Values vol. 34 no. 2</ref> * [[Africa Source]], open source workshop .<ref>"African Free and Open Source Software Developers Meeting March 15th - 19th." Africa News</ref><ref>"Africa Source II - Free and Open Source Software for Local Communities." Africa News.</ref> * "10 Tactics for Turning Information into Action," a 50-minute film that shows "how social justice organizations in the Global South use everything from Google Earth to Facebook in their campaigns."<ref>Derek Blackadder. "Twitter & Toodledo." Our Times, Feb/March 2010.</ref><ref>[http://www.informationactivism.org/en 10 Tactics]. Retrieved 2011-10-13</ref><ref>Mary C. Joyce, ed. Digital activism decoded: the new mechanics of change. NY: International Debate Education Assoc., 2010</ref>
